05015nam a22006255i 9780822386308DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1229161651  a97808223863087 a10.1515/97808223863082doi  a(DE-B1597)554334  a(OCoLC)1125547349  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aThomas, Deborah A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModern Blackness :bNationalism, Globalization, and the Politics of Culture in Jamaica /cDeborah A. Thomas; ed. by Sonia Saldívar-Hull, Irene Silverblatt, Irene Silverblatt. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America otherwise : languages, empires, nations : 4600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction ‘‘Out of Many, One (Black) People’’ -- tPART I The Global-National -- tChapter 1 The ‘‘Problem’’ of Nationalism in the British West Indies; or, ‘‘What We Are and What We Hope to Be’’ -- tChapter 2 Political Economies of Culture -- tPART II The National-Local -- tChapter 3 Strangers and Friends -- tChapter 4 Institutionalizing (Racialized) Progress -- tChapter 5 Emancipating the Nation (Again) -- tPART III The Local-Global -- tChapter 6 Political Economies of Modernity -- tChapter 7 Modern Blackness; or, Theoretical ‘‘Tripping’’ on Black Vernacular Culture -- tConclusion The Remix -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aModern Blackness is a rich ethnographic exploration of Jamaican identity in the late twentieth century and early twenty-first. Analyzing nationalism, popular culture, and political economy in relation to one another, Deborah A. Thomas illuminates an ongoing struggle in Jamaica between the values associated with the postcolonial state and those generated in and through popular culture. Following independence in 1962, cultural and political policies in Jamaica were geared toward the development of a multiracial creole nationalism reflected in the country’s motto: “Out of many, one people.” As Thomas shows, by the late 1990s, creole nationalism was superseded by “modern blackness”—an urban blackness rooted in youth culture and influenced by African American popular culture. Expressions of blackness that had been marginalized in national cultural policy became paramount in contemporary understandings of what it was to be Jamaican.Thomas combines historical research with fieldwork she conducted in Jamaica between 1993 and 2003. Drawing on her research in a rural hillside community just outside Kingston, she looks at how Jamaicans interpreted and reproduced or transformed on the local level nationalist policies and popular ideologies about progress. With detailed descriptions of daily life in Jamaica set against a backdrop of postcolonial nation-building and neoliberal globalization, Modern Blackness is an important examination of the competing identities that mobilize Jamaicans locally and represent them internationally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEthnicityzJamaica. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectszJamaica. 0aIdentity (Psychology)zJamaica. 0aNationalismzJamaica. 0aPolitics and culturezJamaicaxHistory. 0aPopular culturezJamaica. 0aSocial classeszJamaica. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverblatt, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.o